      "solution": "def karnaugh(Column:int=1) -> list[str]:\n    # Base case if n is equal to 1\n    if Column == 1:\n        return ['0', '1']\n    \n    # Initialize the gray list\n    gray_code:list[str] = karnaugh(Column-1)\n\n    # Invert the actual sequence\n    reflected_gray_code:list[str] = gray_code[::-1]\n\n    # Concat the two sub sequences\n    gray_code = ['0' + code for code in gray_code] + ['1' + code for code in reflected_gray_code]\n\n    return gray_code\n\nprint(' '.join(karnaugh(int(input())))[:1000])",
      "statement": "In telecommunications and electronics, Gray Code is often used to reduce data transmission errors. Since consecutive values differ by only one bit, it minimizes the risk of errors when transitioning from one value to another.\n\nAnd guess what ? You are in charge to make a script to generate a sequence of gray code of 2^[[N]] size.\n\nTo do this, you can use the property that states Gray code is generated by taking the previous sequence with a 0 in front of each value and adding to it the reverse sequence with a 1 in front of each value.\n\n\nFor exemple, with [[N]] = 2, the process would be like :\n\n- Starting with : 0, 1\n\n- Make a list with 0 in front of each item of the list : 00, 01\n\n- Do the same with 1 and revert it :\n     - add the 1 :   10, 11\n     - revert it :      11, 10\n\n- Concatenante the two lists : 00, 01, 11, 10\n\nGray code with [[N]] = 2 is : 00 01 11 10",
